<font color="#FF0000">HIT AND RUN</font><br>
<tt>Wed Jan 29 23:12:23 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Mike T.:<br><br>
Great!<br><br>
Another &quot;hit and run&quot; on the scene.<br><br>
The formula:<br><br>
1. I don't like something here.<br>
2. This is the way I think it should be.<br>
3. This is the way I think you should think.<br>
4. I don't care what you think.<br>
5. I don't care what you think about me.<br>
6. Here is some guilt on which you can trip out.<br>
7. You are the one being the antagonist.<br>
8. Repeat as often as required to stomp on everyone.<br><br>
'Nam really holds on to everyone, doesn't it. Everyone seems to have an albatross hung around their neck. Some albatrosses stink more than others, though.<br><br>
It seems that there are as many ways of trying to deal with the pain as there are people. Anger always works the best. It is safe, effective, feels good, and impersonal. In the end, it always destructively consumes the person using it, eventually.<br><br>
I have anger about Vietnam. A lot of very real anger. I get angry with people who try to cram their own personal Vietnam opinion and agenda down my throat, and try to make me feel guilty if I do not share the same view. I get down right pissed off. I even go into a rage now and then. My PTSD even gets cranked up to wide open throttle.<br><br>
                        *but*<br><br>
I am here to listen, learn, and express my feelings, and not be a schoolyard bully. I will find here some of the validation that was stolen from me or outright denied. I will even make a few friends. That feels good.<br><br>
If we survived the real bullets, then we can survive the ones in our heads!<br><br>
Mike T., you are OK, and I am OK, and to hell with the rest of them. Remember that. I will never forget Vietnam either. I can't. <br><br>
Peace  <br>

<p><code>-- art16@ix.netcom.com  (Arthur Varanelli) </code><p>


